                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/1625: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Everett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-07-10T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 10, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 10—1:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>190. Consulate’s 186, June 30, 6 p.m. From another source I have obtained a
                    somewhat fuller statement of the position in the Mandates Commission. The
                    Commission approached the problem from two points of view.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Is the policy laid down in the British White Paper compatible with the
                        Mandate as interpreted in the past by the British Government or the League
                        Council or the Mandates Commission? On this point all members of the
                        Commission except Lord Hankey agreed that the question must be answered in
                        the negative, and this was so recorded in the Commission’s report.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Would the Commission now, in view of the changed circumstances surrounding
                        the Mandate, be justified in considering the announced British policy as
                        compatible with the Mandate? The position on this point and the action taken
                        were as described in my telegram under reference.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Everett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
